message.content:
 You can use CSS Flexbox to horizontally align divs. Here's an example where we create a container with three child divs and use 'display: flex;', 'justify-content: flex-end;' to align the divs to the right:

HTML:
```html
<div class="container">
  <div class="item">Item 1</div>
  <div class="item">Item 2</div>
  <div class="item">Item 3</div>
</div>
```
CSS:
```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: flex-end; /* Aligns divs to the right */
}

.item {
  margin: 10px; /* To make it visible, can be removed as per requirement */
  background-color: #f2f2f2;
  padding: 5px;
  border-radius: 5px;
}
```
In this example, the 'justify-content' property is set to 'flex-end'. This property aligns its children along the horizontal line that runs from left to right. It puts the end of the line at the leftmost part of the container and spreads the children along the remaining space towards the right.
